let optionalString: String? = "Hello, world!"

if let unwrappedString = optionalString {
    print("The unwrapped string is: \(unwrappedString)")
} else {
    print("The optional string is nil.")
}
/*In this example, optionalString is an optional String that may or may not have a value. Using if let, we create a new constant unwrappedString and assign it the non-nil value of optionalString if it exists. The code block inside the if let statement will only execute if optionalString has a non-nil value. If optionalString is nil, the code block inside the else statement will execute.

This pattern helps you write safer and more predictable code by ensuring that you only access and work with non-nil values when working with optionals.
*/